      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. I'll clarify how sharps and flats are represented around the Circle of Fifths.\n\nAs you move clockwise around the Circle of Fifths, key signatures start acquiring sharps. If you start at C major (with no sharps or flats), as you move clockwise to G major, you add F sharp. Continuing clockwise through D, B, E, A, and C♯ major, you continue to accumulate sharps. Here's a simplified rundown of what happens:\n\n- C major: No sharps or flats.\n- G major: F♯\n- D major: F♯, C♯\n- B major: F♯, C♯, G♯\n- E major: F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯\n- A major: F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯, A♯\n- D minor: F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯, A♯\n- G minor: F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯, A♯, E♯\n\nAs you continue to circle around, you'll notice",
